re exists a complex give and take between distribution methods that merely copy existing songs (such as counterfeit CDs) and ones that transform songs into new products (such as file sharing). Ultimately, he contends, it was the music industry’s persistent lagging behind in creating innovative products that led to the very piracy it sought to eliminate.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aCopyrightxMusiczUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aMusic tradexCorrupt practiceszUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aPiracy (Copyright)zUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aPopular musicxWriting and publishingxCorrupt practiceszUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aSound recording industryxCorrupt practiceszUnited StatesxHistory. 0aSound recordingsxPirated editionszUnited StatesxHistory. 7aMUSIC / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311063538640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226431840423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780226431840.jpg  a978-3-11-063538-6  University of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles